                                <condition>
                                    <p>The stone is fragmentary and damaged with the surface severely abraded at points.However as Forsyth notes <q>'only a small portion has been lost'</q> (1996,375). Interestingly, the patterns of wear suggest a full life with a potential of time in the sea.</p>
                                </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>
                                    <p>The stone is one of six located inside the Lochgoilhead parish church in Lochgoilhead and Kilmory. The church has frst been recorded at the closing of the 14th century and later sources Forsyth traces, amount it as a dedication to the Three Holy Brethen. The <name xml:id="S-ARL-004">Loghgoilhead</name> ogham stone itself looks unfinished with possibly various different hands crafting each letter over periods of time. Forsyth comments that <q>'Perhaps the block of stone was selected for carving then...abandoned ending up as chisel-fodder'</q> (1996,375). The ogham inscription itself is located on edge C of the RCAHMS diagram, to the right of the groove as part of two lines of lettering. The upper appears to be roman while the lower is in the ogham alphabet.</p>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>
                                <p>
                                    The stem-line of the inscription is <height unit="cm">19.5</height> long, running parallel to the edge of the stone. The individual strokes are of varying length between <height unit="cm">2.0 and 3.5</height> and <width unit="cm">0.3 and 0.6</width>.The inscription is <rs type="execution" key="carved" ref="https://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/168.html">carved</rs>.The carving is as Forsyth observed <q>'course and scrappy, doubtless because of the intractability of the stone and the subsequent abuse the block has suffered.'</q> (1996,377).The begining and end of the inscription are badly worn making any reading of those portions uncertain.
                                </p>
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
