            <div type="commentary">
                 <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1">
                        <p>If the suggested reading is correct it could be interperted as the personal name MUD-MALI. The first element may be from the adjective muad meaning noble or good while the second element may be correlated to the common personal name MAGL which normally found in compound names such as this one. As Forsyth comments <q>Although there is no extant example of the two elements MOD/MUAD and 
MAGL-/MAL together, the combination is theoretically possible, perhaps with meaning 'noble prince'</q> (1996, 380-381).</p>
                    </item>
                     <item n="2">
                         <p>If the fifth letter is not M as the suggested reading implies then another possibility offered by Forsyth is the interpertation VALI from the root wal meaning to be strong, a very common element in celtic personal names (1996, 382).</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="3">
                         <p>If letter 5 is a modified A then the potential reading Forsyth purposes is the Mudali. It is important to note that these readings do not exhaust all possibilities. A better understanding in how the three texts (the groove, the roman and the ogham inscription) relate to one another would assist a more accurate interpertation.</p>
                     </item>
                     <item n="4">
                         <p>The difficulty in defining the original purpose of the Lochgoilhead stone has led to many explanations of which, as Forsyth comments one<q>'is no more implausible than any other'</q> (1996, 383).</p>
                     </item>
                 </list>
            </div>
